cs.CV, cs.LG, cs.AI, cs.CL, cs.MM 

This paper deals with unsupervised domain adaptation for object recognition and semantic segmentation tasks, which are typically studied in the computer vision (cs.CV) and machine learning (cs.LG) communities. The proposed method involves introducing unlabeled bridging domains to connect the source and target domains, which is a novel approach to reducing domain discrepancy. This could also be relevant to the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) community, which is interested in developing algorithms that can adapt to new environments. The paper also mentions using discriminators to reduce discrepancies, which is a technique commonly used in natural language processing (cs.CL) and multimedia (cs.MM) research.
